\section{Introduction}
%% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

This report analyses a single-phase variable reluctance machine (VRM)
analytically and through finite element analysis (FEA).
The machine consists of a rectangular laminated-steel stator core and a
D-shaped rotor. As the rotor rotates, the magnetic circuit reluctance
changes, producing a net electromagnetic torque.

The objectives of this project are:
\begin{enumerate}[label=\textbf{\arabic*.}]
  \item Derive analytically the inductance and torque as functions of
        rotor angle under constant DC excitation.
  \item Model the machine in 2D FEA with linear material properties and
        compare with the analytical results.
  \item Repeat the 2D FEA with non-linear (saturating) material properties.
  \item Propose a control method to achieve continuous unidirectional
        rotation.
\end{enumerate}

