\subsection{Assumptions}

The following simplifying assumptions are made for Part Q1:

\begin{enumerate}[label=\alph*)]
  \item \textbf{Infinite core permeability} ($\mu_r \to \infty$): core
        reluctance is negligible; only the air-gap reluctance matters.
  \item \textbf{No fringing flux}: the effective flux cross-section equals
        the geometric core cross-section at every rotor position.
  \item \textbf{Uniform flux distribution}: flux density is uniform
        across the core cross-section.
  \item \textbf{Sinusoidal inductance variation}: the inductance varies
        sinusoidally with twice the mechanical rotor angle, a standard
        first-order approximation for a 2-pole machine.
  \item \textbf{Lossless magnetic circuit}: eddy-current and hysteresis
        effects are neglected.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Core Geometry Calculations}

\subsubsection{Core Cross-Sectional Area}

The core cross-section is rectangular with width
$w_c = 15\unit{mm}$ and depth $d = 25\unit{mm}$:

\begin{equation}
  A_{\mathrm{core}} = w_c \times d
    = 15 \times 25 = 375\unit{mm^2}
    = 375 \times 10^{-6}\unit{m^2}
  \label{eq:Acore}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Mean Core Path Length}

The mean magnetic path length is computed along the centre-line of the
stator yokes and legs:

\begin{align}
  \ell_{\mathrm{core}}
    &= 2\,(w_w + w_c) + 2\,(h_w + w_c) \notag \\
    &= 2\,(30 + 15) + 2\,(40 + 15) \notag \\
    &= 90 + 110 = 200\unit{mm} = 0.2\unit{m}
  \label{eq:lcore}
\end{align}

Under the infinite-permeability assumption, core reluctance is zero
and $\ell_{\mathrm{core}}$ does not enter the inductance calculation.
It is used in the non-linear extension of Section~\ref{sec:improve}.

\subsubsection{Air-Gap Lengths}

The magnetic flux crosses \textbf{two air gaps in series} (from stator
into rotor and back). The total effective gap length varies between a
minimum (aligned) and a maximum (unaligned) value.

\paragraph{Aligned position ($\theta = 0^{\circ}$).}
The curved arc of the D-rotor faces both stator pole tips.
Each gap equals the design clearance:
\begin{equation}
  \ell_{g,\min} = 2g = 2 \times 0.5 = 1\unit{mm}
  \label{eq:lgmin}
\end{equation}

\paragraph{Unaligned position ($\theta = 90^{\circ}$).}
The flat face of the D-rotor faces the stator pole tips.
Each effective gap increases to $2.5\unit{mm}$:
\begin{equation}
  \ell_{g,\max} = 2 \times 2.5 = 5\unit{mm}
  \label{eq:lgmax}
\end{equation}

\subsection{Reluctance and Inductance at Extreme Positions}
\label{sec:LmaxLmin}

With infinite core permeability the circuit reluctance equals the
air-gap reluctance alone:

\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{R} = \frac{\ell_g}{\mu_0 \, A_{\mathrm{core}}}
  \label{eq:reluctance}
\end{equation}

and the self-inductance is:

\begin{equation}
  L = \frac{N^2}{\mathcal{R}}
    = \frac{N^2 \,\mu_0 \,A_{\mathrm{core}}}{\ell_g}
  \label{eq:inductance}
\end{equation}

\subsubsection{Maximum Inductance -- Aligned ($\theta = 0^{\circ}$)}

\begin{align}
  \mathcal{R}_{\min}
    &= \frac{\ell_{g,\min}}{\mu_0\, A_{\mathrm{core}}}
     = \frac{1 \times 10^{-3}}{4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times 375 \times 10^{-6}}
     = 2.122 \times 10^{6}\unit{A/Wb}
  \label{eq:Rmin} \\[6pt]
  L_{\max}
    &= \frac{N^2}{\mathcal{R}_{\min}}
     = \frac{300^2}{2.122 \times 10^{6}}
     = 42.41\unit{mH}
  \label{eq:Lmax}
\end{align}

\subsubsection{Minimum Inductance -- Unaligned ($\theta = 90^{\circ}$)}

\begin{align}
  \mathcal{R}_{\max}
    &= \frac{\ell_{g,\max}}{\mu_0\, A_{\mathrm{core}}}
     = \frac{5 \times 10^{-3}}{4\pi \times 10^{-7} \times 375 \times 10^{-6}}
     = 10.610 \times 10^{6}\unit{A/Wb}
  \label{eq:Rmax} \\[6pt]
  L_{\min}
    &= \frac{N^2}{\mathcal{R}_{\max}}
     = \frac{300^2}{10.610 \times 10^{6}}
     = 8.48\unit{mH}
  \label{eq:Lmin}
\end{align}

The ratio $\mathcal{R}_{\max}/\mathcal{R}_{\min}
= \ell_{g,\max}/\ell_{g,\min} = 5$, so
$L_{\min}/L_{\max} = 1/5$.
