\subsection{Inductance Variation as a Function of Rotor Angle}
\label{sec:Ltheta}

Under the sinusoidal approximation, the inductance at an arbitrary
mechanical angle $\theta$ is:

\begin{equation}
  \boxed{L(\theta) = \frac{L_{\max}+L_{\min}}{2}
    + \frac{L_{\max}-L_{\min}}{2}\cos(2\theta)}
  \label{eq:Ltheta}
\end{equation}

This satisfies the boundary conditions:
$L(0^{\circ}) = L_{\max} = 42.41\unit{mH}$ and
$L(90^{\circ}) = L_{\min} = 8.48\unit{mH}$.
The factor $2\theta$ reflects the two-pole symmetry: inductance
completes one full cycle every $180^{\circ}$ of mechanical rotation.

The computed inductance variation is plotted in the top panel of
Figure~\ref{fig:LT_plots}.

\subsection{Torque Derivation}
\label{sec:torque}

For a lossless system with constant current excitation, the
electromagnetic torque follows from the co-energy derivative
(which equals the field energy derivative for a linear system):

\begin{equation}
  T(\theta) = \frac{1}{2}\,i^2\,\frac{dL(\theta)}{d\theta}
  \label{eq:Tcoenergy}
\end{equation}

Differentiating Equation~(\ref{eq:Ltheta}):

\begin{equation}
  \frac{dL}{d\theta} = -(L_{\max}-L_{\min})\sin(2\theta)
  \label{eq:dLdtheta}
\end{equation}

Substituting into Equation~(\ref{eq:Tcoenergy}):

\begin{equation}
  \boxed{T(\theta) = -\frac{i^2}{2}\,(L_{\max}-L_{\min})\,\sin(2\theta)}
  \label{eq:Ttheta}
\end{equation}

With constant $i = I = 2.5\unit{A}$, the peak torque amplitude is:

\begin{align}
  T_{\mathrm{peak}}
    &= \frac{I^2}{2}\,(L_{\max}-L_{\min}) \notag \\
    &= \frac{(2.5)^2}{2} \times (42.41 - 8.48) \times 10^{-3} \notag \\
    &= \frac{6.25}{2} \times 33.93 \times 10^{-3}
     = 106.0\unit{mN \cdot m}
  \label{eq:Tpeak}
\end{align}

The average torque under constant DC excitation is zero because
positive and negative half-cycles cancel over a complete revolution.
Continuous rotation requires switched excitation
(Section~\ref{sec:control}).

The torque profile is plotted in the bottom panel of
Figure~\ref{fig:LT_plots}.

