\subsection{Suggestions to Improve the Analytical Model}
\label{sec:improve}

\subsubsection{Finite Core Permeability (Linear)}

When the core permeability is finite ($\mu_r < \infty$), the core
reluctance must be added in series with the air-gap reluctance:

\begin{equation}
  \mathcal{R}_{\mathrm{total}}
    = \underbrace{\frac{\ell_g}{\mu_0 A_c}}_{\text{air gap}}
    + \underbrace{\frac{\ell_{\mathrm{core}}}{\mu_0 \mu_r A_c}}_{\text{core}}
  \label{eq:Rtotal}
\end{equation}

For a typical silicon-steel grade ($\mu_r \approx 5000$) this
reduces $L_{\max}$ by a few percent and modifies the
$L_{\max}/L_{\min}$ ratio.

\subsubsection{Non-Linear (Saturating) Core}

Real electrical steels have a non-linear $B$--$H$ characteristic.
At high flux densities the core saturates and $\mu_r$ falls sharply.
Inductance then depends on both $\theta$ and $i$:
$L = L(\theta, i)$.  Torque must be evaluated from the general
co-energy integral:

\begin{equation}
  T = \left.\frac{\partial W'(\theta,i)}{\partial\theta}\right|_{i=\mathrm{const}},
  \qquad
  W' = \int_0^{i} \lambda(\theta, i')\,di'
\end{equation}

where $\lambda$ is the flux linkage. Both $L_{\max}$ and $L_{\min}$
are reduced relative to the infinite-permeability case, and the torque
profile deviates from a pure sinusoid.

\subsubsection{Fringing Flux Correction}

Fringing flux at the air-gap edges effectively increases the
cross-section seen by the flux.  A common empirical correction adds one
gap length to each linear dimension of the pole face:

\begin{equation}
  A_{c,\mathrm{eff}} \approx (w_c + \ell_g)\,(d + \ell_g)
  \label{eq:fringing}
\end{equation}

Because $\ell_g$ differs between aligned and unaligned positions,
the fringing correction modifies the $L_{\max}/L_{\min}$ ratio.
A 2-D or 3-D FEA simulation captures this effect automatically.

\subsubsection{Position-Dependent Pole Overlap}

The sinusoidal approximation is a first-order model.  A more accurate
description accounts for the actual change in overlapping pole arc
area with angle, yielding a piece-wise linear or trapezoidal inductance
profile.  This can be computed analytically by integrating the air-gap
permeance over the overlapping area as a function of $\theta$.

