\section{Q4 -- Control Method for Continuous Rotation}
\label{sec:control}
%% ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

\subsection{Problem Statement}

Under constant DC excitation the torque given by
Equation~(\ref{eq:Ttheta}) averages to zero over one full revolution.
To obtain net unidirectional rotation the coil current must be switched
in synchrony with the rotor position.

\subsection{Switched DC Excitation Strategy}

From Equation~(\ref{eq:Ttheta}), torque is positive
(rotation in the direction of increasing $\theta$) when:

\begin{equation}
  \sin(2\theta) < 0
  \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
  \theta \in (90^{\circ},\,180^{\circ})
  \;\cup\;
  (270^{\circ},\,360^{\circ})
\end{equation}

The coil is therefore energised with $I = 2.5\unit{A}$ only when the
rotor moves from the \textbf{unaligned toward the aligned position}, and
de-energised otherwise.

\subsection{Average Torque with Switched Excitation}

With ideal on/off switching (current on at $\theta = 90^{\circ}$,
off at $\theta = 180^{\circ}$, repeated each half-cycle), the
average positive torque is:

\begin{align}
  T_{\mathrm{avg}}
    &= \frac{1}{\pi}\int_{90^{\circ}}^{180^{\circ}}
       \frac{I^2}{2}\,(L_{\max}-L_{\min})\,
       \bigl[-\sin(2\theta)\bigr]\,d\theta \notag \\[4pt]
    &= \frac{T_{\mathrm{peak}}}{\pi}
       \left[\frac{\cos(2\theta)}{2}\right]_{90^{\circ}}^{180^{\circ}} \notag \\[4pt]
    &= \frac{T_{\mathrm{peak}}}{\pi}
       \left(\frac{1}{2} - \left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\right)
     = \frac{T_{\mathrm{peak}}}{\pi}
     \approx \frac{106.0}{\pi}
     \approx 33.8\unit{mN \cdot m}
  \label{eq:Tavg}
\end{align}

This is approximately $1/\pi \approx 31.8\%$ of the peak torque.

\subsection{Practical Implementation}

In practice the switching instants must account for:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Turn-on advance angle}: current cannot rise
        instantaneously; the coil must be energised slightly before
        $\theta = 90^{\circ}$ to allow current to build up.
  \item \textbf{Turn-off advance angle}: the coil must be switched off
        before $\theta = 180^{\circ}$ (aligned) to avoid braking torque
        during the current tail-off.
  \item \textbf{Position sensing}: a Hall-effect sensor or incremental
        encoder detects rotor position for synchronised switching.
  \item \textbf{Current regulation}: a PWM chopper maintains constant
        current during the on-interval, keeping the torque profile close
        to the ideal sinusoidal shape derived analytically.
\end{itemize}

